<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / Germans reduce Treasury bill rate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESSURES inside the European exchange rate mechanism eased again yesterday
after the Bundesbank surprised some currency dealers by announcing a large
cut in the interest rate of one of its money market instruments.
The Bundesbank cut the interest rate on its 3-day Treasury bill by 90 basis
points to 7.5 per cent.
The move came a week after the Bundesbank cut its discount rate by 50 basis
points, also to 7.5 per cent.
Some dealers described the move as a significant easing of policy by the
Bundesbank because the Treasury bill rate is sometimes seen as marking the
effective floor for all rates in the German cash market rates.
Mr Jonathan Hoffman, an economist at Credit Suisse First Boston in London,
said the cut was significant because the cost of borrowing D-Marks overnight
has been at comparatively high levels recently.
Money Markets, Page 35
</TEXT>
