<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / Government to save 12 pits: British Coal told to start
preparations for industry's privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH and RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yesterday instructed British Coal immediately to begin
preparations for privatisation as it unveiled plans by the company to
reprieve 12 of 31 threatened pits and provide a hope of rescue for another
seven.
Another 12 pits where British Coal intends to stop mining will be offered to
the private sector to run along with the seven mothballed pits. Legislation
for full privatisation is likely to be brought forward in the next
parliamentary session for implementation in 1995.
Presenting a white paper on coal, Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry
secretary, told the House of Commons that the private sector would play a
critical role in the coal industry. 'We believe that privatisation is the
only way of enabling this industry to take full advantage of the
opportunities the market offers.'
The government's partial climbdown over pit closures means that an
additional 5,800 jobs will be lost in the short term on top of 8,000 miners
who have taken redundancy since last October. The total of nearly 14,000 job
losses compares with more than 30,000 which were expected when the
government announced its original pit closures plan last October.
The revised plan was attacked by supporters of the coal industry and unions
which viewed it as a short-term fix which would provide only a temporary
reprieve for most of the 12 pits as it failed to create more room in the
energy market for coal.
Mr Norman Willis, Trades Union Congress general secretary, described the
white paper as a 'deliberate deception' and said it signalled the demise of
the coal industry. 'The reality is that 18 pits will shut down immediately
and the remainder will be closed within two years.'
Mr Heseltine announced that the electricity industry had agreed to buy 160m
tonnes of coal over five years from British Coal. He expected the deals to
be signed by the end of March. He also committed the government to
subsidise, by an unspecified amount, additional sales by British Coal to the
electricity industry. The subsidy would bridge the gap with world prices but
would last only until privatisation.
The trade and industry select committee suggested in January that up to
Pounds 500m would be needed over five years to subsidise tonnages above base
contracts. Yesterday's white paper was imprecise, saying the government
would embrace the committee's range of figures for subsidies.
The generators are discussing the size of extra contracts with British Coal
but are resisting anything above 40m tonnes over five years. That would
provide a future for a few of the 12 pits.
Mr Neil Clarke, British Coal chairman, would not predict how many of the 12
reprieved pits would last following a market testing exercise to determine
extra sales. Negotiations will be complicated by the government's decision
to encourage the private coal-mining sector which will increase competition.
Mr Heseltine also announced that the Connah's Quay gas project in north
Wales and two smaller gas projects should be allowed to go ahead. These
projects would involve investment of over Pounds 2bn and would lead to the
creation of over 5,000 construction jobs, he said.
They will further erode the potential market for coal. In addition, Mr
Heseltine said the market for coal would diminish for environmental reasons.
The European Commission gave its broad approval to the white paper after
telephone discussions between Mr Heseltine and the two commissioners
responsible for the sector, Mr Abel Matutes, energy commissioner, and Mr
Karel Van Miert, who is in charge of competition policy.
The detailed programme will still have to be submitted to the Brussels
authorities and receive the formal approval of all 17 commissioners.
Mr Heseltine announced that two pits - Bolsover in Derbyshire and Sharleston
in Yorkshire - would close because of 'impending exhaustion'. Ten pits where
production has already ceased will not reopen.
COAL WHITE PAPER: THE MAIN POINTS
Twelve pits to be closed, 12 to be reprieved, six to be mothballed, one to
have development work only.
Generators to buy 160m tonnes over five years from British Coal; government
to subsidise additional sales.
Privatisation of British Coal to be speeded up.
Subsidies to be phased out before privatisation; all pits to be offered for
sale or lease before being closed.
Total of Pounds 200m to help areas affected by closure.
Magnox nuclear power stations to be kept open and nuclear review brought
forward a year.
'Dash for gas' to continue with no restrictions on gas-fired power stations;
three projects get go-ahead
No restrictions on French sales of electricity to the UK.
New energy panel to offer advice on development of markets; government to
publish an annual energy review.
More money for research into clean coal technology.
