<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / Yeltsin announces tough economic package
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and DMITRI VOLKOV
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE REFORMIST Russian government of President Boris Yeltsin last night
unveiled a proposed package of stringent economic measures, before the
country's conservative-dominated parliament gathers today to debate Mr
Yeltsin's future.
The measures, including higher interest rates and a moratorium on foreign
debt repayments, would be enacted by presidential decree under powers
assumed by Mr Yeltsin on Wednesday.
Their announcement came after a cabinet meeting at the end of a day which
brought an abrupt about-turn by Mr Ruslan Khasbulatov, the parliamentary
speaker. Moves to impeach Mr Yeltsin for exceeding his authority appeared
unlikely after Mr Khasbulatov said he was no longer in favour of this
action.
'Frankly speaking, I'm no supporter of impeachment,' Mr Khasbulatov told
reporters. This follows his declaration on Tuesday that the case for
impeachment was 'as clear as day'.
But, a direct confrontation between the president and parliament is still
possible at today's Congress of People's Deputies.
Mr Sergei Shakhrai, deputy prime minister, said he expected the parliament
instead to invoke a constitutional clause which strips the president of his
powers if he tries to disband or suspend other elected institutions.
The deputies, said Mr Shakhrai, would be invited by Mr Khasbulatov to
resolve to bring this clause into play if Mr Yeltsin continued his
confrontation with them - and would clarify the clause by laying down that,
in that case, the office of president would pass to General Alexander
Rutskoi, currently vice-president.
Such a procedure might not require the two-thirds majority needed for
impeachment, and which the conservatives had been struggling to reach.
The impact on the congress today of the government's seizing of the economic
initiative could not immediately be gauged. The severity of the other
measures was tempered by a proposed 50 per cent increase in the minimum wage
for state employees to Rbs4,500 a month.
But the package was clearly too much even for some cabinet members. It was
tabled in the absence of prime minister, Mr Victor Chernomyrdin, who was
absent from the meeting to meet the visiting Slovak leadership.
Chief among the dissenters was Mr Victor Gerashchenko, the chairman of the
central bank and ex-cabinet member. Earlier yesterday he received a letter
from Mr Boris Fyodorov, deputy prime minister for the economy and finance,
warning him he intended to seek Mr Gerashchenko's dismissal for failing to
act in accordance with government policy. Mr Gerashchenko said he would
return any future such messages without reading them.
Russia in turmoil, Page 2
</TEXT>
<XX>
