FT  26 MAR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Is it really sheer chance that tonight's Arena on BBC2 happens to clash with
Heartburn on BBC1? Arena sets out to challenge the pretence that 'any
resemblance between the characters portrayed in this book and any person
living or dead is entirely coincidental'. The programme attempts to discover
who is really supposed to be who in fiction, and 'where writers draw the
line between literature and stitching up their friends, not to mention
getting revenge on their enemies' (9.30). Meanwhile Heartburn (9.30) offers
a big-screen version of the book by Nora Ephron, which is all about a
marriage between Washington media folk. The marriage is ruined by an affair
between the husband, a journalist, and a diplomat's wife. Since Ephron was
married to Watergate journalist Carl Bernstein there has never been too much
mystery about who was really being portrayed. Unfortunately even though Jack
Nicholson and Meryl Streep play the couple it is not the greatest of films.
Radio 3 has an unusual concert of music by Ravel, played by the BBC Welsh SO
(7.30).
