<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Revised strategy holds back Reckitt - Extra
marketing costs for brand promotion could be found from productivity gains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CHANGE in strategy towards more promotion of its brands and new product
development held back 1992 profits at Reckitt &amp; Colman, the household goods
group.
Sir Michael Colman, chairman, said that despite difficult trading conditions
the results 'exhibited the strength of the brands behind this business which
have held up remarkably well'.
Pre-tax profits for the year to January 2 on the old accounting basis were
slightly lower at Pounds 248.3m (Pounds 252.3m), although profits reported
under FRS 3 were down sharply to Pounds 181.7m (Pounds 234m).
The FRS 3 figure included trading losses of Pounds 9.6m from the US spice
and seasoning business. The Pounds 47.3m cost of selling it last summer hit
profits as did a Pounds 9.6m reorganisation charge.
Sir Michael said the proposed increase in the final dividend to 10.25p would
give a 7.3 per cent increase in the total to 16.2p (15.1p) reflecting the
policy of consistent dividend growth.
He said the rise also showed the board's confidence in the revised strategy,
although he admitted that the short-term effect would be to hold back
profits.
Mr Vernon Sankey, chief executive, said extra marketing costs could be found
from productivity gains and margins had been maintained at high levels.
Operating margins from continuing businesses were 15.2 (15.1) per cent.
Group sales were Pounds 1.9bn (Pounds 1.99bn) although those from continuing
business were virtually unchanged at Pounds 1.85bn. Operating profits from
continuing operations were Pounds 281.7m (Pounds 280.7m) and total operating
profits were Pounds 272.1m (Pounds 292.6m). Interest charges were Pounds
33.5m (Pounds 40.3m).
Earnings fell to 25.16p (37.9p) on an FRS 3 basis or 40.51p (41.76p) on SSAP
6.
Operating profits in the UK rose 2.2 per cent to Pounds 70.1m, with improved
productivity raising margins from 18.8 to 19.7 per cent. In the rest of
Europe profits fell from Pounds 79.1m to Pounds 71.6m as recession began to
affect the business. North American profits fell 5.5 per cent to Pounds
39.6m as the costs of launching a new electric air freshener cut the margin.
Profits from Australasia and Asia fell from Pounds 42.3m to Pounds 40.5m,
despite strong growth in south-east Asia. Profits from Africa rose by a
third to Pounds 28.2m and from Latin America by 14.6 per cent to Pounds
31.7m.
Mr Iain Dobbie, finance director, said exchange rate moves had added Pounds
58.1m to its foreign currency borrowings, though the profit and loss
account, which uses average rates, had hardly been affected. There should be
a significant currency benefit this year.
COMMENT
Reckitt's solidity is ideal in recessions. The new strategy, first outlined
last year, appears sensible. And the conservatism of the management is
comforting. However, unlike Colman's mustard, the shares are not going to
light fires in investors' hearts for a while. Once the brand promotion
strategy begins to come through to profits, though, the shares should do
well, especially with the progressive dividend policy. Forecasts are in the
Pounds 280m to Pounds 290m area, for a p/e of about 13.5.
</TEXT>
