<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / Slough Estates plans rights issue after 59% rise to Pounds
50m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SLOUGH Estates, the UK's largest industrial property company, yesterday took
advantage of the City's improved sentiment towards the property sector by
launching a Pounds 147.3m rights issue to reduce its gearing.
The rights issue was accompanied by a 59 per cent rise in 1992 pre-tax
profits from Pounds 31.6m to Pounds 50.3m, a 17 per cent decline in diluted
net assets per share from 331p to 274p and a 30 per cent cut in the
dividend.
Slough Estates' share price, which has nearly doubled since interest rates
began to fall last September, dipped 2p to 193p.
Sir Nigel Mobbs, chairman, was cautiously optimistic about the property
market. 'We believe that the market is at or near its bottom,' he said.
However, he doubted that there would be a significant improvement until the
rise in unemployment was arrested.
Sir Nigel said the rights issue was necessary to reduce the 'higher than
appropriate' balance sheet gearing, which increased from 67 per cent to 83
per cent during 1992.
The rights issue will reduce gearing to 58 per cent and dilute the net asset
value from 276p to 245p.
The proposed 3-for-10 rights issues involves the issue of 100.8m new shares
at 150p each. The company also said it was redeeming its 6 per cent
convertible bonds due in 2003.
The operating profit before interest and exceptional items increased from
Pounds 95.7m to Pounds 114.0m. Net interest charges increased from Pounds
27.4m to Pounds 44.9m, with a Pounds 20.2m decline in capitalised interest.
Exceptional provisions against trading property assets amounted to Pounds
18.8m, compared with Pounds 36.7m in 1991. Property sales totalled Pounds
123m.
The value of its investment portfolio fell by 10.1 per cent. Values fell by
7.3 per cent in its core UK industrial portfolio, by 8.2 per cent in its UK
retail portfolio and by 21.1 per cent in its UK office portfolio.
Bredero Properties, which is 49.5 per cent owned by Slough, has began talks
with its banks about renegotiating its loans. Slough has valued its
investment at Pounds 13.3m. Earnings per share rose from 8p to 9.6p. The
final dividend of 5p (up from 7.15p) makes a total dividend for the year of
8.1p (up from 11.55p).
Lex, Page 20
