<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STOCK index futures maintained a healthy premium to the underlying cash
market throughout the day in spite of a sharp retreat brought about by a
sell programme in the first half of the session, writes Joel Kibazo.
Having opened at 2,867, the March contract moved sharply ahead to 2,875 on
news that the Bundesbank had cut its interest rate on its 3-day Treasury
bills to 7.5 per cent.
That momentum quickly faded as dealers instead focused on the big sell
programme, said to have come from UBS Phillips &amp; Drew. This led to
persistent selling of the contract and the June contract recorded a low of
2,840 for the day.
The firm opening in New York, together with sizeable buying from a leading
US house helped the June contract to recover.
There was a 10-20 point premiumfor most of the day and the June contract
closed at 2,870, 3 points below its close on Wednesday and 13 points above
its estimated fair value to cash of around 9 points. Turnover was around
10,000 contracts.
Dealings in traded options were quite heavy and volume closed at 41,576
lots. Some 6,348 contracts were dealt in the FT-SE 100 option and 3,059 in
the Euro FT-SE 100 option. Among the stock options, Dixons led the way with
2,136 contracts and was followed by Prudential at 1,981 lots.
</TEXT>
