<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / Cable TV group to seek phone licences
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A GROUP of cable television companies operating throughout the UK is about
to apply to the government for a licence to offer personal communications
network (PCN) services.
Six cable TV investors want to offer mobile services in their areas, the
newspaper Communications Week International says.
If they are successful, it would be the cable operators' first entry to the
mobile communications market, and could lead to increased competition in a
mass market for low-cost pocket radio-telephones and related services.
The six companies - Comcast, Diamond Cable, General Cable, Nynex, Pacific
Telesis and Southwestern Bell - believe their existing networks will enable
them to provide mobile services quickly and relatively cheaply.
General Cable, a subsidiary of the French water utility Compagnie Generale
des Eaux, claims that it could make PCN services available within nine
months at competitive prices.
The Cable TV Association, which represents the companies, is urging the
government to give them the block of radio air space freed last year by the
merger of Mercury Personal Communications and Unitel.
Existing PCN licence holders Hutchison Telecom, Mercury One-2-One, Vodafone
and Cellnet are likely to oppose the granting of the licence, arguing that
it is not cost-effective to provide PCNs on a local basis.
The Department of Trade and Industry has yet to decide whether to issue new
PCN licenses.
</TEXT>
