<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / Change of image for stainless steel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE STAINLESS Steel Fabricators' Association, which represents 180 companies
in the UK stainless industry, has relaunched itself as the British Stainless
Steel Association as part of a new assault on the marketplace.
Mr Dick Wakelin, chairman of the association, said the change was more than
cosmetic. Many member companies are not fabricators; they are stockholders,
manufacturers, owners of foundries or involved with finishing.
The association says its main aim is to promote the use of stainless steel
in all its forms. Stainless is the only ferrous metal whose use in western
markets is predicted to grow this decade.
Through greater promotional activity, the association wants to increase the
use of stainless steel in the UK to be nearer that of Japan and other
leading industrialised countries. Japan uses 16kg per head per year while
the UK uses only 5kg.
The discovery of stainless steel was one of the world's first defence
industry spin-offs. Sheffield metallurgist Harry Brearley was examining the
excessive wear of rifle barrels and observed that steel with a high chromium
content would not rust.
</TEXT>
