<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / International Company News: IBM shares fall on worries over
pricing and succession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE, NIKKI TAIT and Our Financial Staff
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO, NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in International Business Machines fell sharply in New York yesterday
afternoon, apparently as a result of growing concern about pricing pressures
on the computer-makers's mainframe business.
IBM's stock closed Dollars 3 1/8 lower at Dollars 51 1/8 on heavy trading of
more than 3.2m shares. IBM said its policy was not to comment on the stock's
activity.
Traders said investors also appeared disappointed by reports that Mr Louis
Gerstner, chairman of RJR Nabisco, the US food and tobacco company, had
emerged as a leading candidate for the top job at IBM amid rising
speculation that IBM could shortly name a new chief executive officer.
Mr Michael Metz, an analyst at Oppeneimer, said: 'My guess is there's a lot
of scepticism on whether (Mr Gerstner) can do the job.'
RJR Nabisco declined to comment on reports of Mr Gerstner's impending
departure yesterday. IBM also declined to comment on reports that Mr
Gerstner has had several meetings with IBM's selection committee of
non-executive directors. The committee was formed in January when Mr John
Akers, IBM chairman and chief executive, said he would step down as chief
executive following IBM's announcement of Dollars 4.9bn losses for 1992, its
second consecutive annual loss.
Under US securities laws, IBM has to make an announcement as soon as it has
made a final selection and reached contractual arrangements. The lack of
such an announcement suggests no final decision has been made.
Other potential candidates, including Mr John Sculley of Apple Computer, Mr
Larry Bossidy of Allied-Signal and Mr George Fisher of Motorola, have issued
statements saying they would not take the job.
The selection of Mr Gerstner would suggest that IBM's board has decided the
company needs stronger financial controls rather than new technology
leadership, since Mr Gerstner has no experience in the computer industry.
He was named as chief executive of RJR Nabisco in March 1989, shortly after
the record Dollars 25bn leveraged buyout of the food and tobacco giant.
Then 47, he moved to the company from American Express, which he had joined
in 1978 as president of the card division, and risen to become chairman of
the executive committee of the parent company in 1983, and then president in
1985.
Mr Gerstner has no direct prior ties to IBM, but his brother, Mr Richard
Gerstner, is a former IBM senior executive. He retired recently for health
reasons.
</TEXT>
