<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Threats mar Maastricht victory
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH, IVOR OWEN and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO FRESH threats to the passage of the Maastricht bill emerged yesterday on
an evening which ended on a high note for the government, when it won a
procedural vote to extend debate on the measure into the small hours.
One setback came from Labour, which tabled a new amendment that could force
the government to choose between accepting the social chapter and being
unable to ratify the treaty.
The second occurred when it emerged that Tory Euro-sceptics received legal
advice at a meeting on Tuesday which encouraged them to seek judicial review
of the attorney-general's opinion about the impact of a separate Labour
amendment.
Last month, Sir Nicholas Lyell, the attorney-general, surprised MPs by
contradicting Foreign Office lawyers' advice that accepting the amendment,
which excludes the social chapter from the bill, would wreck the treaty. If
the amendment is passed, the Tory rebels are now determined to challenge his
view.
The new Labour amendment would prevent the ratification bill coming into
force until the Commons had decided whether the social chapter should apply
to the UK. This would mean a separate debate after the bill completed its
parliamentary passage.
The government's morale boost came when the support of 17 Liberal Democrats
helped it to a comfortable majority of 17 (296 votes to 279) on a division
to extend the 17th day of detailed Commons discussion of the bill beyond
10pm.
A total of 26 Tory rebels, five Ulster Unionists, two Scottish Nationalists
and one Lib Dem voted with Labour against the extension.
Mr Tristan Garel-Jones, the European affairs minister, said: 'We remain on
course to complete the committee and report stages before the Danish
referendum (May 18) and take the third reading immediately afterwards.'
Labour is confident that its new clause on the social chapter is within
Westminster's procedural rules.
The decision about whether the Commons should debate it rests with Mr
Michael Morris, the deputy Speaker.
It would, however, be a tortuous process to reach the point at which the
government had to choose between not going ahead with Maastricht and
adopting the social chapter.
To get there, Tory Euro-sceptics would have to vote explicitly for the
social chapter - which they do not support - in the hope that ministers'
vehement opposition to the chapter would mean that the government would
prefer not ratifying to adopting it.
But if that were the choice, the government would come under severe pressure
from many Tory backbenchers to accept the social chapter rather than wreck
the treaty.
That is because they believe more jobs would be lost through a fall in
inward investment if the UK did not sign up to Maastricht than would be lost
because of the impact of the social chapter.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
    P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Government News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
