<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / Swansea barrage completed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SWANSEA yesterday marked the completion of a river barrage, the first such
barrage in the UK, with a campaign to promote the way in which the city is
changing its legacy of industrial dereliction.
The barrage, built at a cost of Pounds 17m with Pounds 6.5m coming from the
European regional development fund, is at the mouth of the river Tawe. At
low tide the river has been a muddy eyesore.
Water is now retained by the barrage for four miles upstream, improving its
appearance and, the council hopes, its attraction to developers which it is
seeking for 23 sites near the river.
Locks allow boats to enter a 600-berth marina at all states of the tide, and
a fish ladder enables fish to swim upstream to spawn. Seals have already
been observed above the fish pass.
The barrage, which has to cope with a tidal range of 8.6 metres, one of the
highest in the world, also generates up to 100kw of electricity for the
national grid.
</TEXT>
