FT  25 MAR 93 / German steel pay talks fail
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GERMAN steel employers and unions have failed to find a compromise to avert
a strike in eastern Germany next month.
Inconclusive talks were held this week between IG Metall, Germany's giant
engineering union, and the steel employers association. The union is
insisting on a 21 per cent pay increase for its 20,000 steel union members
in eastern Germany, as part of a March 1991 contract. The employers have
offered 9 per cent.
IG Metall said yesterday it would start balloting members in eastern Germany
on a strike, although one senior official conceded that the union 'did not
really want a strike' in eastern Germany.
Small and medium-sized enterprises did not want a strike, he said, nor could
they pay their employees a 26 per cent rise. However, it was time 'the
workers in eastern Germany learned to defend their interests. After 50
years, they have forgotten how to strike.'
