<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / The Lex Column: Kingfisher
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Kingfisher's decision to extend its everyday low pricing policy at B&amp;Q looks
like the market leader tightening the screw on the competition. The timing,
just ahead of the crucial Easter trading period, is certainly tactical. But
the strategy depends upon longer term performance improvements which the
others will find hard to match. Texas may find a refuge in the softer home
furnishings and decoration area. Do It All has nowhere to run. Only the high
costs of exit will prolong the agony.
Kingfisher's other big idea is Europe. The Darty acquisition is proof of
this commitment, but the proposition still seems suspect. If markets are
becoming increasingly similar, then how can Darty's high margins in France
be squared with Comet's weaker showing in the UK? Any convergence seems
likely to be in the direction of lower, not higher margins.
</TEXT>
