<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / Companies to be required to revalue assets regularly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES will be required to revalue regularly most of the assets shown in
their accounts, under radical proposals issued yesterday by the body which
sets accounting standards in the UK.
They will need to show properties, quoted investments and commodities in
their balance sheets at current values which are updated every few years,
according to two documents from the Accounting Standards Board.
Mr David Tweedie, chairman of the board, said: 'The balance sheet does not
make sense. This will reduce the scope for manipulation by companies and
remove a lot of discretion.'
He said he would like to see full revaluations of assets every five years,
and 'desktop' or partial revaluations every year.
The action will halt the practice by which companies can leave assets
undervalued on their balance sheets by showing them at their original
purchase price or historical cost. It will also hit companies with
properties which they have revalued but which are now overvalued because of
the slump in property prices.
It is likely to generate opposition from companies during consultation in
the coming months that revaluations will be costly and subjective.
But a survey commissioned by the board last year showed that 70 per cent of
companies already revalue operating properties and 83 per cent had done so
within the past five years. The board's discussion document says the three
options for valuation are to return to historical cost accounting, introduce
full current values or address existing anomalies.
The board favours the latter option, saying historical cost accounting would
be regressive and full current values would be extremely costly and unlikely
to gain support from companies.
But in a separate draft chapter of the board's statement of principles - on
which its standards are based - it calls ultimately for a move to regular
revaluations of all assets and liabilities at the current value to the
business.
The statement also calls for the introduction of the concept of 'capital
maintenance' which would reflect the true value of a company's capital over
time.
But Mr Tweedie said: 'This is the agenda for the unforeseeable future. At
the moment we are just moving modestly to clean up the present system.'
The role of valuation in financial reporting. Pounds 5. Statement of
principles Chapter 5. Free. ASB, Holborn Hall, 100 Gray's Inn Road, London
WC1X 8AL.
Accountancy column, Page 13
</TEXT>
