<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Labour moves on social chapter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR has tabled a new amendment to the Maastricht bill, which could leave
the government with the choice between having to accept the social chapter
or being unable to ratify the treaty.
The amendment would prevent the ratification bill coming into force until
the House of Commons had decided whether the social chapter should apply to
the UK. This would mean a separate debate after the bill itself had
completed its parliamentary passage.
In a further threat to the government, it emerged that at a meeting on
Tuesday, Tory Euro-sceptics received legal advice which encouraged them to
seek judicial review of the attorney-general's opinion about the impact of a
separate Labour amendment.
Last month, Sir Nicholas Lyell, the attorney-general, surprised MPs by
contradicting Foreign Office lawyers' advice that accepting the amendment,
which excludes the social chapter from the bill, would wreck the treaty. If
the amendment is passed, the Tory rebels are now determined to challenge his
view.
Labour is confident that its new clause on the social chapter is within
Westminster's procedural rules.
The decision about whether the Commons should debate it rests with Mr
Michael Morris, the deputy Speaker.
The new clause is being carefully studied by other opposition parties and by
Tory rebels, but it would be a tortuous process to reach the point at which
the government had to choose between not going ahead with Maastricht and
adopting the social chapter.
To get there, Tory Euro-sceptics would have to vote explicitly for the
social chapter - which they do not support - in the hope that ministers'
vehement opposition to the chapter would mean that the government would
prefer not ratifying to adopting it.
But if that were the choice, the government would come under severe pressure
from many Tory backbenchers to accept the social chapter rather than wreck
the treaty, since they believe that more jobs would be lost through a fall
in inward investment if the UK did not sign up to Maastricht than would be
lost because of the impact of the social chapter.
One possibility would be for the Tory rebels to vote for the amendment to
the bill without committing themselves on how they would vote in the
subsequent debate on the social provisions.
In the Commons itself, on the 17th day of detailed discussion of the bill,
government hopes of speeding up progress were given a boost when Liberal
Democrat MPs helped it to secure a majority of 57 to curtail a debate on the
role of the European Court of Justice.
Tory Euro-sceptics repeatedly challenged claims by Mr Tristan Garel-Jones, a
foreign office minister, that the court had already adapted to a less
centralised role and was taking increasing account of the views of
individual national governments.
</TEXT>
