<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / Carey calls for commitment to urban renewal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REPEATED government changes in funding arrangements for urban regeneration
programmes need to be replaced by a sustained commitment, Dr George Carey,
archbishop of Canterbury, said yesterday.
Dr Carey, on a visit to Liverpool, said the regeneration of stricken urban
areas was a long-term project, with hope and confidence gathering painfully
slowly.
'The experience of too many voluntary organisations engaged in partnerships
with government agencies in employment, training, self-help and other urban
projects has been of the tap turning on and off,' he said.
'Funding regimes have chopped and changed. Programmes have been mounted,
encouraged, cut and scrapped. Destabilising reviews of the Urban Programme
have been carried out every couple of years.'
Dr Carey said he believed many private companies would have similar
complaints.
All parties to urban regeneration partnerships needed patience and sustained
commitment to a shared task.
While recognising the financial and political pressures involved, it was
difficult to have a steady relationship with a partner who was too restless
and changeable.
'We need a more sustained and secure government contribution towards the
long haul of turning round our deep urban problems,' the archbishop said.
</TEXT>
