<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / Probe uncovers police racism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVIDENCE that managers in the police force are ignoring cases of serious
sexual harassment and are even joining in 'racist banter' has been uncovered
by an official investigation into equal opportunities in the police service,
published yesterday by the Home Office.
Strong evidence that women police offers were 'suffering persistent
low-level harassment unchecked by supervisors', was found by Her Majesty's
Inspectorate of Constabulary.
The inspectorate also found 'evidence of personal physical harassment which
had been brought to the attention of supervisors and had not been dealt
with'.
Some senior managers were not prepared to recognise harassment as a problem
and victims had no faith that grievance procedures would protect them from
further victimisation and isolation by their colleagues, according to the
investigation.
The study was based on a sample of 12 of the 43 forces in England and Wales,
and covered more than 35,000 officers out of a total of 127,000. 12 per cent
of police officers in England and Wales are women. Interviews were held with
police officers and civilian employees of all grades.
The inspectors report that during the meetings with officers, including
supervisors, 'it was obvious that an underlying level of racist banter was
accepted; supervisors were unprepared to challenge or, worse, were prepared
to join in'.
The report says that one force collected no data on recruitment, while in
another there was a wide disparity one year between failure rates for male
applicants (56.5 per cent) and female applicants (73.2 per cent). The report
notes: 'Of equal concern, the force was unable to offer any explanation for
this.'
Study of recruitment literature found 'a considerable domination of white
male images', and there was little evidence of special efforts being made to
attract ethnic minorities to the forces inspected.
There was no evidence of specialist posts being officially closed to women
or ethnic minorities, although women were found to be 'seriously
underrepresented in mainstream CID posts', the report notes.
A small number of women interviewed 'thought the pendulum of equal
opportunities had swung too far and that men were being discriminated
against, particularly in terms of promotion', it concludes.
</TEXT>
