<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / Court blow to contracting-out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE High Court yesterday delivered a further blow to the government's
contracting-out programme when it declared that the Transfer of Undertakings
Regulations (Tupe) did apply to a prison education service being transferred
from a Local Education Authority.
The Brussels-inspired Tupe regulations aim to protect the pay and conditions
of employees when undertakings are transferred from one employer to another.
But there is wide disagreement about precisely when Tupe applies in
contracting-out.
The Home Office had advised that Tupe would not apply in the case of prison
education services, and education providers had tendered on that basis.
Yesterday's judgement from Sir Michael Ogden that Tupe did apply in the case
of Kenny versus South Manchester College contradicts that Home Office
advice.
Lawyers also said it casts doubt on the recent guidance from Mr William
Waldegrave, the public service minister, who said Tupe would not normally
apply when the new employer conducts the operation without making
significant use of previous staff, premises or equipment.
The case was brought by two members of the college lecturers' union Natfhe,
Mr Peter Kenny and Ms Helen Woodruff. They were challenging the fact that
South Manchester College, which has won the contract to provide education at
the Thorn Cross Young Offenders Institute, was not committed to taking on
staff who had been providing the education and were offering different
contracts.
South Manchester College, which may appeal, will now have to take on staff
who had been employed by Cheshire County Council and on the same terms and
conditions.
The prison service will have to meet demanding performance targets when it
becomes a semi-autonomous agency in a week's time, Mr Kenneth Clarke, the
home secretary, said last night.
He made it clear that he expected standards to improve but warned that there
would be no extra resources and stressed the need for more efficient working
practices.
</TEXT>
