<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / Bank hints it should lose 'protector' role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bank of England hinted yesterday that its role as protector of bank
depositors should be devolved to an outside institution.
In a speech on bank supervision, Mr Brian Quinn, the director in charge of
supervision, said that present arrangements for supervising and regulating
banks 'may have to be reconsidered'.
Although his speech gives few details on this issue, it is understood that
Mr Quinn believes there is a distinction to be drawn between his
department's two main functions: the protection of the financial system and
the protection of depositors.
Under the 1979 and 1987 Banking Act, the Bank has explicit responsibility
for both functions. However, he said that the depositor protection function
has encouraged bank customers to believe that 'the banking supervisor is
there to protect them from every deficiency they experience - or perceive -
in the service they get from their bank'.
But he was adamant this was not his role: 'I have to say that the role of
the banking supervisor is to seek to enforce prudent conduct by banks, not
customer satisfaction.'
Mr Quinn stressed that the bank is a supervisor but not a regulator. He
defined regulation as the process of ensuring that financial institutions
follow appropriate rules when selling financial products, to protect
consumers from buying bad or unsuitable products.
The Securities and Investments Board and the self-regulatory organisations
act as regulators of banks when they sell non-deposit products and services,
such as life policies or shares.
But there is a regulatory vacuum in deposit taking and lending services.
Mr Quinn is understood to believe that there is an argument for giving the
Bank's deposit-protection functions to an outside body - though not until
the present reorganisation of the regulation of investment and life products
is completed. However, he did not make this view explicitly in the speech.
He did argue that the Bank should retain its role as supervisor, in the
sense of ensuring that there is the minimum risk of a collapse in the
payments system. Although he said that there is a potential conflict between
the Bank's role as the executor of monetary policy and its role as
supervisor, he believes that there are advantages to combining the
functions.
Lord Alexander, chairman of National Westminster Bank, said for the first
time that his bank would join the Personal Investment Authority, the
proposed new regulator of the retail investment industry,
if the PIA could demonstrate that it would be an efficient and effective
regulator.
The Bank of England yesterday supported the winding up of a small company
which had been operating illegally as a bank and is thought to have taken
deposits of about Pounds 1m. The Bank supported a petition in the High Court
from the landlords of General Credit Finance. It said it wanted to hear from
depositors of GCF.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>General Credit Finance.
</CO>
<XX>
