<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / Relief over polluted land decision
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, and BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE withdrawal of the government's plans to introduce a contaminated land
register was greeted yesterday with widespread relief tempered by
uncertainty about what might replace it.
Businesses, developers and local authorities had been convinced that the
proposed registers would blight land, depress land prices and be a severe
setback to urban regeneration. Pressure on the government to withdraw its
proposals came from groups ranging from the Confederation of British
Industry to the Council of Mortgage Lenders. 'We are delighted that the
proposals have been withdrawn. They would have had a disastrous effect on
many small businesses,' said Mr Marco Torquati of the Association of British
Chambers of Commerce.
But some critics believed the government's announcement of a 'new
wide-ranging review of the problems in this area' would merely prolong the
uncertainty that has damaged the property market.
'We were expecting a firm announcement at this stage,' said Mr Michael
Chambers of the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors. 'This is rather a
disappointment. There will now be a long period of uncertainty.'
Mr Chris Smith, Labour's spokesman on the environment, said a third round of
consultation and review meant the government had given no sign of fulfilling
its legal obligation under the Environmental Protection Act of 1990. 'It
leaves still a considerable amount of uncertainty,' he said.
After two consultations, the government has collected the views of some 400
environmentalists, landowners and consultants involved in the debate.
The review will consider the powers and duties of public authorities
relating to contaminated land, the mechanisms for recovering authorities'
costs in remedying pollution, the statutory changes needed and whether any
longer-term studies should be put in place.
Some commentators believe the principle of the register should be salvaged.
Mr Smith said he did not want to see the principle of a register thrown away
completely. 'I want to see a proper register that allows land to be taken
off it.' Otherwise, he said, the entire burden of assessing whether land was
fit for development would fall on local authorities.
</TEXT>
