<TEXT>
THE regulation of securities markets should be centralised under the
Securities and Investments Board, Sir Andrew Hugh Smith, chairman of the
London Stock Exchange, said yesterday, Richard Waters writes.
He appealed for a solution to the fragmented regulation built around the
recognised investment exchanges and self-regulatory organisations.
Sir Andrew called for a central database to hold details of all securities
transactions in the UK. SIB should take over investigating and prosecuting
cases extending beyond the remit of any single investment exchange or
self-regulatory body, he said.
Sir Andrew's remarks appear to stem in part from the exchange's experience
in trying to investigate insider dealing.
