<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / Bank suggests shedding its 'protector' role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bank of England hinted yesterday that its role as protector of bank
depositors should be devolved to an outside institution.
In a speech on bank supervision, Mr Brian Quinn, the director in charge of
supervision, said that current arrangements for supervising and regulating
banks 'may have to be reconsidered'.
Although his speech gives few details on this issue, it is understood that
Mr Quinn believes there is a distinction to be drawn between his
department's two main functions: the protection of the financial system and
the protection of depositors.
Under the Banking Act, the Bank has explicit responsibility for both
functions. However, he said that the depositor protection function has
encouraged bank customers to believe that 'the banking supervisor is there
to protect them from every deficiency they experience - or perceive - in the
service they get from their bank'.
But he was adamant this was not his role: 'I have to say that the role of
the banking supervisor is to seek to enforce prudent conduct by banks, not
customer satisfaction'.
Mr Quinn stressed that the bank is a supervisor but not a regulator. He
defined regulation as the process of ensuring that financial institutions
follow appropriate rules when selling financial products, to protect
consumers from buying bad or unsuitable products.
Mr Quinn is understood to believe that there is an argument for giving the
Bank's deposit protection functions to an outside body - though not until
the current reorganisation of the regulation of investment and life products
is completed. However he did not make this view explicitly in the speech.
He did, however, argue that the Bank should retain its role as supervisor,
in the sense of ensuring that there is the minimum risk of a collapse in the
payments system. Although he said that there is a potential conflict between
the Bank's role as the executor of monetary policy and its role as
supervisor, he believes that there are advantages in combining the
functions.
The execution of monetary policy would be impossible if there were problems
with the payments system.
For the first time he made explicit the circumstances in which the Bank acts
as a lender of last resort to a bank. He said that the Bank will only pump
money into a bank if it is 'too important to fail'.
He said that a bank would be allowed to collapse, no matter how big it is,
so long as that collapse did not put the financial system at risk: 'There is
no 'too big to fail' doctrine in the United Kingdom'.
Mr Quinn spoke at a conference on City regulation.
At the same conference, Lord Alexander, chairman of National Westminster
Bank, said for the first that his bank would join the Personal Investment
Authority, the proposed new regulator of the retail investment industry,
if the PIA could demonstrate that it will be an efficient and effective
regulator.
</TEXT>
