<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / MPs mollified while the industry seethes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE press reform proposals yesterday won the backing of MPs who have been
demanding press reform - and were greeted with outrage by the industry.
Most newspapers said they welcomed the recommendations for greater public
access to information but they stressed that the plan to introduce a privacy
bill and to create a statutory press ombudsman and a Press Commission with
powers to fine newspapers would be unwelcome and unworkable.
Mr Clive Soley, the Labour MP whose private Freedom and Responsibility of
the Press Bill returns to the Commons next month, broadly welcomed many of
the proposals.
But he criticised the report's failure to recommend a statutory press
watchdog. 'We are in danger here of buying the press another round in the
Last Chance Saloon,' he said.
Sir Frank Rogers, chairman of the Newspapers Publishers Association and
deputy chairman of The Telegraph group, said: 'They are suggesting the
imposition of a statutory body extremely similar to the Calcutt report
recommendations. It is an extraordinary document - diffuse and even
incoherent.'
Echoing a widespread criticism by the press of the proposed privacy bill,
Sir Frank said: 'If a privacy bill can be constructed it will be extremely
difficult to operate. It's impossible to create anything that would work. A
lot of lawyers have tried and failed.'
He stressed that the privacy bill was not the main bone of contention. 'The
main issue is the statutory body,' he said.
Ms Patsy Chapman, editor of the News of the World, said: 'It looks to me
like layer upon layer of red tape. It doesn't give the industry any credit
for having improved its procedure.'
Lord McGregor, chairman of the Press Complaints Commission, the
self-regulatory body, condemned the planned new body and said that the
proposal for a privacy bill was unworkable.
'I am exceedingly shocked by the extent to which public business is being
conducted by slovenly procedures,' said Lord McGregor, who claimed that the
select committee's report had ignored the government's previous research on
the newspaper industry.
The report's proposal for a system of statutory fines drew criticism across
the board, but plans to control press intrusion drew a more mixed response.
Lord McGregor welcomed the proposal that reporters should identify
themselves, and inform interviewees of their rights.
But Mr Chris Davis, assistant editor of The Sun, said: 'It's basically the
establishment and the MPs trying to look after themselves. We will continue
to harass MPs for breakfast, lunch and dinner.'
</TEXT>
