FT  25 MAR 93 / Fiat group executive faces probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ANOTHER senior member of the Fiat group has been caught up in the corruption
investigations of Milan magistrates.
Yesterday the magistrates revealed that two days ago a cautionary warrant
alleging corruption had been issued against Mr Riccardo Ruggeri, the chief
executive of New Holland, the agricultural machinery and earth moving
venture owned 80 per cent by Fiat and 20 per cent by Ford.
Mr Ruggeri, based at New Holland's headquarters in London, is understood to
have been named by Mr Luigi Caprotti, a former concessionary in Lombardy of
Iveco, Fiat's commercial vehicles group, who had already been questioned by
Milan magistrates. Mr Ruggeri was formerly managing director of Iveco.
Mr Francesco Paolo Mattioli, Fiat's chief financial officer, and Mr Antonio
Mosconi, head of Toro, the Turin group's insurance arm, are being held in a
Milan jail.
