<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / Heseltine woos Tory coal rebels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN, RALPH ATKINS and MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, will today launch a
campaign to win support for his coal white paper, encouraged by the early
reaction of potential Conservative rebels to the broad outline of his
proposals.
At least two of the 11 Tory MPs who failed to support the government when
its pit closure programme was debated in October appeared to have been
brought into line by reports that a package to save or mothball between 12
and 19 of the 31 threatened pits had been agreed.
But there were still concerns that the government was putting in place what
amounted to a short-term political fix, with some of last year's rebels
continuing to pledge defiance.
A meeting of 12 MPs in the coal group of Tory backbenchers was understood to
have agreed to focus on improving the long-term prospects for coal if, as
expected, the subsidies proposed by the government are limited to two years.
As the coal and electricity industries continued their attempts to agree
core contracts on coal supplies, Mr Heseltine was expected to back down from
his previous insistence that these deals be signed before the white paper is
published.
The moment of truth for Mr Heseltine will come when MPs vote on the package
next week. The government was last night considering rescheduling a
previously announced debate on Maastricht to give it the option of
accommodating the coal proposals next Monday.
The white paper - to be called 'The Prospects for Coal' - will be published
today and runs to more than 100 pages. It will be accompanied by an
employment training package for the affected regions, worth up to Pounds
100m.
Under the proposals, pits not earmarked for action could be transferred to
the private sector. Others could be transferred to the private sector under
a speeded-up privatisation programme. The government will offer a subsidy
estimated at between Pounds 5 and Pounds 12 per tonne, as well as proposals
for expanding the coal market by curbing imports.
Officials were emphasising that ministers would not decide which pits
survived. Pits scheduled for closure will still be subject to a statutory
review. The six mothballed pits are likely to include at least some of the
four originally earmarked for mothballing, but then reprieved, last October.
There was scepticism among British Coal managers last night about whether
the white paper would lead to many of the apparently reprieved pits staying
open for as long as two years.
The government won last October's vote with a majority of 13, aided by
Ulster Unionist abstentions.
