<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Clark recommends Berisford
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BATTLE over the future of C&amp;J Clark will now be fought by shareholders
as the company, riven by a boardroom row for several months, yesterday
announced it had chosen Berisford to be the recommended bidder for the shoe
manufacturer owned by the Clark family since 1825.
A main factor in the decision to recommend Berisford, the agribusiness and
property group, appears to have been price. Berisford is thought to have
offered marginally more than Pounds 2 a share, valuing Clark at between
Pounds 157m and Pounds 160m.
Mr Alan Bowkett, Berisford's chairman, said he was delighted to have won the
board's approval to proceed to the next stage of negotiations. 'I am
convinced this represents a marvellous opportunity for both companies to
grow internationally', he said.
Clark will inform shareholders of the formal offer in about two weeks, when
it announces its annual results. It is likely to call an extraordinary
meeting before the annual meeting - now planned for the end of April - to
put the proposals to shareholders.
The sale is expected to be the subject of heated dispute among Clark's 500
family members who control 70 per cent of the group. At least four members
of the 11-strong board - who claim to control more than 30 per cent of the
shares - strenuously object to the loss of family control.
However, a sale has been on the cards since shareholders agreed to find the
best price for the company following a bid approach backed by Electra
Investment Trust.
</TEXT>
